data.content:
Yes! MSTest 3.4+ supports **tuple-based `DynamicData`**, eliminating `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — compile-time type safety
- Array literals `["x", true]` → tuple literals `("x", true)` — no boxing, no casting
- Named tuple elements (`Input`, `Expected`) improve readability in test explorer

This gives you compile-time errors if you accidentally put a `bool` where a `string` belongs, instead of a runtime failure. Requires **MSTest 3.4+** (`MSTest.TestFramework` NuGet package).
